I've worked mostly with java 17 in spring boot appliaction mainly for better performance, cleaner code,
and long-term support(LTS).

1) Records - Used for DTOs
   We used Records for request and response DTOs because they reduce boilerplate code like getters, setters, constructors, equals, and hashCode.

Example:
public record EmployeeDto(Long id, String name, String department){
}

2. Switch Expressions
   We used enhanced switch expressions to make conditional logic cleaner.
    
  String role = switch(userType){
        Case "A" -> "ADMIN";
        Case "M" -> "MANAGER";
        default  -> "USER";
  }

3. Text Blocks
    Used for writing multi-line Sql queries and Json responses.
    String query = """ SElECT id, name FROM employee WHERE status = 'ACTIVE' """;
    @Repository
    public class EmployeeRepository {

      @Autowired
      private JdbcTemplate jdbcTemplate;
  
      public List<Map<String, Object>> getEmployees() {
  
          String sql = """
                  SELECT id,
                         name,
                         department,
                         salary
                  FROM employees
                  WHERE status = 'ACTIVE'
                  ORDER BY salary DESC
                  """;
  
          return jdbcTemplate.queryForList(sql);
        }
    }

4. Pattern Matching of instance of 
    Before Java 17
    if(obj instanceof Employee){
      Employee emp = (Employee) obj;
    }
    Java 17
    if(obj.instanceof Employee emp){
        System.out.println(emp.getName());
    }

5. Sealed Classes
   Used for restricting inheritance in some business validation flows.

    public sealed class Payment permits CardPayment, UpiPayment{}

        public sealed class Payment
            permits CardPayment, UpiPayment {
    
        public void validate() {
            System.out.println("Validating payment");
        }
    }

    public final class CardPayment
            extends Payment {
    
        public void cardDetails() {
            System.out.println("Card payment processing");
        }
    }

    public non-sealed class UpiPayment
            extends Payment {
    }

    *-> Here we used final because: No further inheritance allowed
    
    Keyword	       Meaning
    sealed	       Restricts inheritance
    permits	       Allowed subclasses
    final          No further extension
    non-sealed	   Opens inheritance again

6. Stream API Improvements
   We heavily used Streams for filtering and transforming data.
   employees. stream().filter(Employee::isActive).map(Employee::getName).toList();

  Before java 17 
  @Service
  public class EmployeeService {
  
      @Autowired
      private EmployeeRepository repository;
  
      public List<String> getActiveEmployeeNames() {
  
          List<Employee> employees = repository.findAll();
  
          return employees.stream()
  
                  // Filter active employees
                  .filter(Employee::isActive)
  
                  // Convert Employee object to employee name
                  .map(Employee::getName)
  
                  // Convert stream into List
                  .collect(Collectors.toList());
      }
  }

  Java 17
  return employees.stream()
        .filter(Employee::isActive)
        .map(Employee::getName)
        .toList();
